16. Appendices
16.1 Glossary of Terms
Biosecurity: Management practices that reduce the risk of introduction and spread of disease agents; involves measures to keep diseases out (external biosecurity) and prevent spread within the farm (internal biosecurity).
Compartment: An animal subpopulation contained in one or more establishments under a common biosecurity management system with a distinct health status with respect to a specific disease or diseases for which required surveillance, control and biosecurity measures have been applied.
Disease-Free Compartment Recognition: Official certification that a defined animal subpopulation meets international standards for freedom from specific diseases, enabling preferential trade access.
Zoonotic Disease: An infectious disease that is transmitted between species from animals to humans (or vice versa).
Transboundary Animal Disease (TAD): Epidemic diseases that are highly contagious or transmissible and have the potential for very rapid spread, irrespective of national borders, causing serious socio-economic and possibly public health consequences.
Farm-level Biosecurity: The specific practices and protocols implemented at an individual farm to prevent disease entry and spread.
Extension Worker: Government or NGO staff who provide technical advice and support to farmers in the field.
